>gaut</i>, an ethnic name meaning ‘Geat’ or ‘Goth’; see   Goss  ).","alternatively, perhaps a diminutive of the Old French personal name <i>Josse</i> (Old Breton <i>Judoc</i>); see   Joyce  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph Josselyn was born about 1340, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffery Josselyn, was 19 and his mother, Margaret Rockell, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Patner. He died in 1383, in England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"Abt 1340–1383":"umbes 1340–1383","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1367–1425":"1367–1425","1375–1398":"1375–1398","1323–1373":"1323–1373","1320–1361":"1320–1361","before 1375":"enne 1375","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","From 1360 to 1361":"1360 kuni 1361","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","Bef 1373":"enne 1373","Abt 1383":"umbes 1383","1425":"1425","1367":"1367","1323":"132